2 SENATE BILL 529
1 Section 12–124
2 Annotated Code of Maryland
3 (2022 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
4 BY repealing and reenacting, without amendments,
5 Article – Education
6 Section 15–127
7 Annotated Code of Maryland
8 (2022 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
9 Preamble
10 WHEREAS, Maryland faces a critical shortage of qualified teachers, especially in
11 high–need schools and rural areas such as Southern Maryland where local school systems
12 report persistent vacancies in core subject areas and growing challenges in retaining
13 educators; and
14 WHEREAS, The Blueprint for Maryland’s Future calls for expanding high–quality
15 pathways into the teaching profession, increasing college readiness, and improving
16 workforce pipelines in every region of the State; and
17 WHEREAS, Nationally, early college programs have proven to increase college
18 enrollment, degree attainment, and workforce participation — particularly among
19 first–generation and low–income students — and can be leveraged to build stronger and
20 more diverse teacher pipelines; and
21 WHEREAS, Despite strong national evidence of success, Maryland lags behind most
22 states in providing early postsecondary opportunities for its students; and
23 WHEREAS, As of 2023, Maryland ranked low nationally for dual enrollment
24 participation as a percent of high school enrollment at 10% and ranked low nationally for
25 dual enrollment as a percent of undergraduate enrollment at 7%; and
26 WHEREAS, As of 2022, participation in dual enrollment and early college programs
27 in Maryland is overly concentrated at community colleges with only 5% of students enrolled
28 through public four–year institutions — compared to approximately 28%
29 nationally — limiting exposure to bachelor’s degree pathways, including teacher
30 preparation programs; and
31 WHEREAS, Southern Maryland’s geography, limited access to nearby four–year
32 institutions, and workforce needs make it an ideal region for a program that bridges high
33 schools, community colleges, and the University System of Maryland regional higher
34 education centers to create a seamless teacher preparation pathway; and
35 WHEREAS, Establishing a Southern Maryland Early College Teacher Pathway
36 Program will align with the Blueprint’s goals; now, therefore,

SENATE BILL 529 3
1 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
2 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
3 Article – Education
4 SUBTITLE 22. SOUTHERN MARYLAND EARLY COLLEGE TEACHER PATHWAY
5 PROGRAM.
6 7–2201.
7 IN THIS SUBTITLE, “PROGRAM” MEANS THE SOUTHERN MARYLAND EARLY
8 COLLEGE TEACHER PATHWAY PROGRAM.
9 7–2202.
10 (A) THERE IS A SOUTHERN MARYLAND EARLY COLLEGE TEACHER
11 PATHWAY PROGRAM.
12 (B) THE PURPOSE OF THE PROGRAM IS TO:
13 (1) CREATE A STRUCTURED, CREDIT–BEARING PATHWAY FOR HIGH
14 SCHOOL STUDENTS TO BEGIN PREPARATION TO TEACH PRIMARY AND SECONDARY
15 EDUCATION;
16 (2) EXPAND ACCESS TO AND ENSURE THE AFFORDABILITY OF
17 HIGHER EDUCATION FOR HIGH SCHOOL STUDENTS WHO ARE:
18 (I) HISTORICALLY UNDERREPRESENTED IN HIGHER
19 EDUCATION; AND
20 (II) FROM RURAL AREAS OF THE STATE;
21 (3) BUILD A STRONG AND DIVERSE TEACHER PIPELINE TO SERVE THE
22 STATE’S PUBLIC PRIMARY AND SECONDARY SCHOOLS; AND
23 (4) SERVE AS A MODEL TO BE REPLICATED FOR REGIONAL
24 IMPLEMENTATION STATEWIDE.
25 (C) THE DEPARTMENT, IN CONSULTATION WITH THE MARYLAND HIGHER
26 EDUCATION COMMISSION, SHALL ADMINISTER AND IMPLEMENT THE PROGRAM ON
27 COMPLETION OF THE UNIVERSITY SYSTEM OF MARYLAND’S DEVELOPMENT OF THE
28 PROGRAM IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 12–124 OF THIS ARTICLE.
29 7–2203.

4 SENATE BILL 529
1 A PROGRAM STUDENT SHALL BE CONSIDERED A DUALLY ENROLLED STUDENT
2 FOR PURPOSES OF § 15–127 OF THIS ARTICLE AND MAY NOT BE REQUIRED TO PAY
3 ANY COST THAT IS RELATED TO ENROLLMENT OR PARTICIPATION IN THE PROGRAM,
4 INCLUDING TUITION AND MANDATORY FEES.
5 7–2204.
6 THE DEPARTMENT SHALL ADOPT REGULATIONS TO CARRY OUT THE
7 PROVISIONS OF THIS SUBTITLE.
8 12–124.
9 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
10 INDICATED.
11 (2) “PROGRAM” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN § 7–2201 OF THIS
12 ARTICLE MEANS THE SOUTHERN MARYLAND EARLY COLLEGE TEACHER PATHWAY
13 PROGRAM.
14 (3) “PROGRAM WORKGROUP” MEANS THE SOUTHERN MARYLAND
15 EARLY COLLEGE TEACHER PATHWAY PROGRAM WORKGROUP.
16 (B) IN ACCORDANCE WITH SUBSECTION (C) OF THIS SECTION AND IN
17 CONSULTATION WITH THE DEPARTMENT AND THE COMMISSION, THE UNIVERSITY
18 SHALL DEVELOP THE RECOMMENDATIONS FOR A SOUTHERN MARYLAND EARLY
19 COLLEGE TEACHER PATHWAY PROGRAM AND THE A TEACHER PREPARATION
20 PATHWAY IN SOUTHERN MARYLAND TO:
21 (1) CREATE A STRUCTURED, CREDIT–BEARING PATHWAY FOR HIGH
22 SCHOOL STUDENTS TO BEGIN PREPARATION TO TEACH PRIMARY AND SECONDARY
23 EDUCATION;
24 (2) EXPAND ACCESS TO AND ENSURE THE AFFORDABILITY OF
25 HIGHER EDUCATION FOR ALL HIGH SCHOOL STUDENTS, INCLUDING STUDENTS WHO
26 ARE:
27 (I) HISTORICALLY UNDERREPRESENTED IN HIGHER
28 EDUCATION; AND
29 (II) FROM RURAL AREAS OF THE STATE;
30 (3) BUILD A STRONG AND DIVERSE TEACHER PIPELINE TO SERVE THE
31 STATE’S PUBLIC PRIMARY AND SECONDARY SCHOOLS; AND

SENATE BILL 529 5
1 (4) SERVE AS A MODEL TO BE REPLICATED FOR REGIONAL
2 IMPLEMENTATION STATEWIDE.
3 (C) (1) THE UNIVERSITY SHALL CONVENE A SOUTHERN MARYLAND
4 EARLY COLLEGE TEACHER PATHWAY PROGRAM WORKGROUP TO DEVELOP THE
5 RECOMMENDATIONS FOR THE PROGRAM AND THE TEACHER PREPARATION
6 PATHWAY IN SOUTHERN MARYLAND.
7 (2) THE PROGRAM WORKGROUP SHALL CONSIST OF THE FOLLOWING
8 MEMBERS:
9 (I) ONE REPRESENTATIVE OF THE OFFICE OF THE GOVERNOR,
10 APPOINTED BY THE GOVERNOR;
11 (II) ONE MEMBER OF THE SENATE OF MARYLAND, APPOINTED
12 BY THE PRESIDENT OF THE SENATE;
13 (III) ONE MEMBER OF THE HOUSE OF DELEGATES, APPOINTED
14 BY THE SPEAKER OF THE HOUSE;
15 (IV) THE STATE SUPERINTENDENT, OR THE STATE
16 SUPERINTENDENT’S DESIGNEE;
17 (V) THE CHAIR OF THE ACCOUNTABILITY AND
18 IMPLEMENTATION BOARD, OR THE CHAIR’S DESIGNEE;
19 (VI) THE SECRETARY, OR THE SECRETARY’S DESIGNEE;
20 (VII) THE CHANCELLOR, OR THE CHANCELLOR’S DESIGNEE;
21 (VIII) THE SENIOR VICE CHANCELLOR FOR ACADEMIC AND
22 STUDENT AFFAIRS OF THE UNIVERSITY, OR THE SENIOR VICE CHANCELLOR’S
23 DESIGNEE;
24 (IX) THE EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR OF THE UNIVERSITY SYSTEM
25 OF MARYLAND AT SOUTHERN MARYLAND, OR THE EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR’S
26 DESIGNEE;
27 (X) THE PRESIDENT OF THE UNIVERSITY OF MARYLAND,
28 COLLEGE PARK CAMPUS, OR THE PRESIDENT’S DESIGNEE;

6 SENATE BILL 529
1 (XI) THE PRESIDENT OF TOWSON UNIVERSITY, OR THE
2 PRESIDENT’S DESIGNEE;
3 (XII) THE PRESIDENT OF ST. MARY’S COLLEGE OF MARYLAND,
4 OR THE PRESIDENT’S DESIGNEE;
5 (XII) (XIII) THE PRESIDENT OF THE COLLEGE OF SOUTHERN
6 MARYLAND, OR THE PRESIDENT’S DESIGNEE;
7 (XIII) (XIV) THE COUNTY SUPERINTENDENTS, OR THE COUNTY
8 SUPERINTENDENTS’ DESIGNEES, OF THE FOLLOWING COUNTIES:
9 1. CALVERT COUNTY;
10 2. CHARLES COUNTY; AND
11 3. ST. MARY’S COUNTY; AND
12 (XV) ONE REPRESENTATIVE FROM EACH LOCAL UNION
13 REPRESENTING EDUCATORS IN SOUTHERN MARYLAND, DESIGNATED BY THE
14 UNIVERSITY; AND
15 (XIV) (XVI) ANY OTHER MEMBERS DESIGNATED BY THE
16 UNIVERSITY.
17 (3) ON OR BEFORE JUNE 30, 2029, THE UNIVERSITY SHALL REPORT
18 TO THE DEPARTMENT, THE COMMISSION, THE GOVERNOR, AND, IN ACCORDANCE
19 WITH § 2–1257 OF THE STATE GOVERNMENT ARTICLE, THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY
20 SENATE EDUCATION, ENERGY, AND THE ENVIRONMENT COMMITTEE AND THE
21 HOUSE WAYS AND MEANS COMMITTEE ON:
22 (I) THE PROGRAM WORKGROUP’S RECOMMENDATIONS FOR
23 THE PROGRAM AND THE TEACHER PREPARATION PATHWAY IN SOUTHERN
24 MARYLAND, INCLUDING:
25 1. THE STRUCTURE OF THE TEACHER PREPARATION
26 PATHWAY;
27 2. AN IMPLEMENTATION PLAN FOR THE TEACHER
28 PREPARATION PATHWAY; AND

SENATE BILL 529 7
1 3. ANY LEGISLATIVE OR REGULATORY CHANGES
2 NECESSARY FOR SUCCESSFUL IMPLEMENTATION OF THE TEACHER PREPARATION
3 PATHWAY; AND
4 (II) THE USE OF STATE FUNDS TO DEVELOP THE PROGRAM
5 WORKGROUP’S RECOMMENDATIONS FOR THE PROGRAM AND THE TEACHER
6 PREPARATION PATHWAY IN SOUTHERN MARYLAND.
7 (D) FOR EACH OF FISCAL YEARS 2028 AND 2029, THE GOVERNOR SHALL
8 INCLUDE IN THE ANNUAL BUDGET BILL AN APPROPRIATION OF $250,000 $125,000
9 TO THE UNIVERSITY TO SUPPORT THE DEVELOPMENT OF THE PROGRAM
10 WORKGROUP’S RECOMMENDATIONS FOR THE PROGRAM AND THE TEACHER
11 PREPARATION PATHWAY IN SOUTHERN MARYLAND IN ACCORDANCE WITH THIS
12 SECTION.
13 15–127.
14 (a) (1) In this section, “dually enrolled student” means a student who is dually
15 enrolled in:
16 (i) A secondary school in the State; and
17 (ii) An institution of higher education in the State.
18 (2) “Dually enrolled student” includes a student enrolled in a credit or
19 noncredit certificate or license program, course, or sequence of courses that leads to
20 certification or licensure at an institution of higher education in the State.
21 (b) A public institution of higher education may not charge tuition to a dually
22 enrolled student.
23 (c) Subject to subsection (d) of this section, for each dually enrolled student who
24 is enrolled in a public school in the county, the county board shall pay 75% of the cost of
25 tuition for a public institution of higher education in the State.
26 (d) (1) If there is an agreement before July 1, 2020, between a public school
27 and a public institution of higher education in which the public institution of higher
28 education charges less than 75% of the cost of tuition to a dually enrolled student, the
29 county board shall pay the cost of tuition under the existing agreement.
30 (2) Every 2 years, a public school and a public institution of higher
31 education may evaluate and modify an agreement made under paragraph (1) of this
32 subsection.
33 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
34 1, 2026. It shall remain effective for a period of 4 years and, at the end of June 30, 2030,

8 SENATE BILL 529
1 this Act, with no further action required by the General Assembly, shall be abrogated and
2 of no further force and effect.
